enoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holtby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): habitational name from either of two places called Holtby in North Yorkshire, from the Old Norse personal name <i>Holti</i> + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Holby","meanings":["English (Essex): apparently a habitational name, possibly a variant of   Holtby  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Holtby was born in 1249, in Sessay, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam de Holtby, was 29 and his mother, Mrs Adam de Holtby, was 27. He had at least 1 daughter with Beatrice de Maunby. He died in 1316, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1249–1316":"1249–1316","1251–1316":"1251–1316","1238–Female":"1238–Surnud","1220–1278":"1220–1278","1222–Female":"1222–Surnud","1316":"1316","1249":"1249","1238":"1238","1278":"1278","1222":"1222","1220":"1220","1251":"1251","Thirsk, Yorkshire, England":"Thirsk, Yorkshire, England","<Of, Sessay, Yorkshire, England>":"Sessay, Yorkshire, I